        <h2>Ticketing</h2>
        <h4>The Petro-Canada Canadian Athlete Family Program</h4>
        <p>
            Since Vancouver 2010, Suncor Energy, through its Petro-Canada brand, has helped to ensure that Canadian athletes have family and friends watching them compete live at the Olympic Games. The parameters of the program shift slightly depending on ticket access availability and opportunity provided by each respective Organizing Committee of the Olympic Games (OCOG) but the spirit remains the same.
        </p>
        <p>
            As part of the continued partnership with the Canadian Olympic Committee, Petro-Canada will once again offer family and friends of the athletes the chance to share the Olympic experience in Sochi. That means that Petro-Canada will pay for two tickets (category B or C) for every event that a Canadian athlete competes in.
        </p>
        <p>
            Details of this program will be communicated to the National Sport Federations for Canadian Team Members at a later date. Note that the program is uniquely intended for the families and friends of the athletes and as such, resale of tickets is strictly forbidden. 
        </p>
        <p>
            Please contact <a href="mailto:family&friends@olympic.ca">family&friends@olympic.ca</a> or your NSF F&F Key Contact if you have any questions regarding this program.
        </p>
    <br />
        <h4>Sochi 2014 Ticketing Program</h4>
        <p>In addition to the Athlete Family & Friends tickets being provided by Petro-Canada, The Sochi Organizing Committee (Sochi 2014) will initiate a separate AF&F program that will allow additional access to the purchase of tickets for athletes competing at the Games. These tickets could be used to supplement the Petro-Canada program if 2 tickets per session is not considered sufficient.</p>
        <p>
            Here is information that has been communicated by Sochi 2014 about this program:
<ul><li>Up to 2 tickets will be available per session, per athlete for purchase.
</li><li>Opening or Closing Ceremony tickets are not included in this program
</li><li>The COC is responsible for facilitating the purchase and distribution of all tickets of the Sochi 2014 AF&F Ticketing Program.  Further details on this process will be communicated in November.
</li><li>These tickets can only be sold to family and friends of athletes participating in the Sochi 2014 Winter Olympic Games. They may not be sold to the general public.
    <ul>
        <li>Questions may be asked by Sochi 2014 staff at the venues to ensure the ticket holder is indeed a family member or a friend of an athlete.
    </li>
    </ul>
</li></ul>
Please note that CoSport / Jetset is the only company in Canada that has the rights to re-sell Olympic tickets.  Please also be reminded that anyone using a ticket must also have a valid Spectator Pass.
            

        </p>
       
       
        <h2>Spectator Passes</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>All non-accredited ticket holders will be required to apply for, and validate a spectator pass to access venues.</li>
            <li>The spectator pass will have to be shown with a ticket to enter the venue.</li>
            <li>Application for a spectator pass can occur before or during the Games.</li>
            <li>There will be multiple Validation Centres in Sochi.</li>
            <li>CoSport will provide a specific code for tickets holders to use in their spectator pass registration.</li>
            <li>There will be a help line with English service for issues with the registration site.</li>
            <li>There will be an option to get a spectator pass on site.  It will be fast tracked due to security clearance being done for the visa.  This would indicate that a spectator pass is not needed to get a visa.</li>
            <li>Further updates are expected in the fall of 2013 and the COC will communicate the final process when available.</li>
        </ul>
        <h2>Migration Cards</h2>
        <p>
            In order to enter Russia, you must present a completed migration card.
        </p>
        <p>
            Migration cards will generally be distributed on the plane or on the train before your arrival or directly at the port of entry into Russia. They are also available at the airport prior to passport control.
        </p>
        <p>
            Generally, your migration card must be completed before proceeding to passport control. Please note that in some cases, they will complete it for you at passport control.
        </p>
        <p>
            A Migration card must be filled by each international visitor, irrespective of age.
        </p>
        <p>
            Please verify that the date that gets stamped on your Migration Card (and in your passport) is accurate before leaving the airport.
        </p>
        <p>
            You must ensure to keep your Migration card safe and not lose it as you need to hand it in when you leave Russia at the end of your trip.
        </p>
        <p>
            If the Migration Card is lost or damaged, please inform the Russian migration authorities on the same day so that the card can be reissued. In some cases, hotel staff could help facilitate this for you. If you experience difficulties please let your NSF F&F coordinator know so they can work with the COC to resolve it. 
        </p>
        <p><a href="/pdf/coc-sample_migration_card_en.pdf" target="_blank">Click here for an example of a Migration Card</a></p>
        <h2>What to Pack</h2>
        Important information<br /><br />
        <ul>
    
            <li>Allowable weight allowance for luggage is 50lbs (check with your airline)</li>
            <li>Pack a pair of comfortable shoes and/or boots</li>
            <li>Bring a change of clothes and any essential toiletries in your carry-on</li>
        </ul><br />
        Other optional handy items to take along<br /><br />
